INSERT INTO ActiveSymbols VALUES (1,'The AUD Basket is a financial metric used to gauge the relative strength of the Australian dollar (AUD) in comparison to a group of five major global currencies: the United States Dollar (USD), Euro (EUR), British Pound (GBP), Japanese Yen (JPY), and Canadian Dollar (CAD). In this basket, each of these currencies carries equal weight, constituting 20% of the overall measurement.','synthetic_index','WLDAUD',3,'AUD Basket','forex_basket','Derived','Australian Dollar Basket'),
	(2,'AUD/CAD, denoting the exchange rate between the Australian Dollar (AUD) and the Canadian Dollar (CAD) in the forex market, holds significant relevance for traders and investors. The AUD serves as the base currency, with the CAD as the quote currency, reflecting how many Canadian Dollars are required to purchase one Australian Dollar. This currency pair is particularly notable due to its ties to commodity markets, given that both Australia and Canada are major commodity exporters. Movements in commodity prices, interest rate differentials set by the Reserve Bank of Australia and the Bank of Canada, economic data releases, global market sentiment, and technical analysis all influence the AUD/CAD exchange rate. Traders employ various strategies to navigate this dynamic currency pair, making it a valuable asset for diversification and trading opportunities in the forex arena.','forex','frxAUDCAD',5,'AUD/CAD','minor_pairs','Forex','Australian Dollar/Canadian Dollar'),
	(3,'AUD/CHF is a forex currency pair that reflects the exchange rate between the Australian Dollar (AUD) and the Swiss Franc (CHF). Within this pairing, the AUD is considered the base currency, and the CHF is the quote currency. Essentially, AUD/CHF indicates how many Swiss Francs are needed to buy 1 Australian Dollar. If the AUD/CHF pair is trading at 0.6800, it signifies that 1 AUD can be exchanged for 0.6800 CHF. Traders and investors utilize AUD/CHF to speculate on the relative strength of these two currencies, either buying it with optimism that the Australian Dollar will appreciate against the Swiss Franc or selling it if they anticipate the opposite scenario. The exchange rate for AUD/CHF is influenced by various factors such as economic data releases from Australia and Switzerland, disparities in interest rates, geopolitical events, and broader market sentiment. Traders closely analyze these factors to make informed decisions within the forex market. ','forex','frxAUDCHF',5,'AUD/CHF','minor_pairs','Forex','Australian Dollar/Swiss Franc'),
